body:
# Redis Streams

Redis Streams is an append-only log structure for durable event processing. Unlike [[redis/pub-sub]], streams persist messages, support replay from any point, and provide consumer groups for distributed processing with acknowledgment. Connect using the configuration in [[redis#connection]].

## Add and Read

```javascript
import Redis from "ioredis";

const redis = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);

// Add an entry to a stream (auto-generated ID with *)
const messageId = await redis.xadd("orders", "*",
  "orderId", "ORD-1234",
  "product", "widget",
  "quantity", "3",
  "status", "created"
);
console.log(`Added with ID: ${messageId}`); // e.g. 1681234567890-0

// Read entries from a stream (from the beginning)
const entries = await redis.xrange("orders", "-", "+");
for (const [id, fields] of entries) {
  console.log(`${id}:`, fields); // fields is [key1, val1, key2, val2, ...]
}

// Read new entries (blocking, waits up to 5 seconds)
const newEntries = await redis.xread("BLOCK", 5000, "STREAMS", "orders", "$");

// Read from a specific ID forward
const fromId = await redis.xread("COUNT", 10, "STREAMS", "orders", "1681234567890-0");
```

## Consumer Groups

Consumer groups distribute stream entries across multiple consumers for parallel processing:

```javascript
// Create a consumer group (start from beginning with 0, or latest with $)
await redis.xgroup("CREATE", "orders", "order-processors", "0", "MKSTREAM");

// Read as a consumer within a group
// Each consumer gets unique entries — no duplicates across consumers
const entries = await redis.xreadgroup(
  "GROUP", "order-processors", "worker-1",
  "COUNT", 10,
  "BLOCK", 5000,
  "STREAMS", "orders", ">"
);

// Process entries
if (entries) {
  for (const [stream, messages] of entries) {
    for (const [id, fields] of messages) {
      // Process the message...
      console.log(`Processing ${id}:`, fields);

      // Acknowledge successful processing
      await redis.xack("orders", "order-processors", id);
    }
  }
}
```

### Consumer Group Lifecycle

```
Producer ── XADD ──> Stream ── XREADGROUP ──> Consumer A ── XACK ──> Done
                          ├── XREADGROUP ──> Consumer B ── XACK ──> Done
                          └── XREADGROUP ──> Consumer C ── XACK ──> Done
```

Each entry is delivered to exactly one consumer in the group. If a consumer fails without acknowledging, the entry remains in the **pending entries list (PEL)** and can be claimed by another consumer.

## Acknowledgment

```javascript
// Acknowledge processed entries
await redis.xack("orders", "order-processors", messageId);

// Check pending entries (not yet acknowledged)
const pending = await redis.xpending("orders", "order-processors");
// Returns: [totalPending, smallestId, largestId, [[consumer, count], ...]]

// Get detailed pending entries for a consumer
const pendingDetail = await redis.xpending(
  "orders", "order-processors", "-", "+", 10, "worker-1"
);

// Claim entries from a failed consumer (idle > 60 seconds)
const claimed = await redis.xclaim(
  "orders", "order-processors", "worker-2",
  60000, // min idle time in ms
  pendingMessageId
);
```

## Trimming

Control stream size to prevent unbounded growth:

```javascript
// Trim to approximately 1000 entries (efficient, uses ~ for approximate)
await redis.xtrim("orders", "MAXLEN", "~", 1000);

// Trim to exact count
await redis.xtrim("orders", "MAXLEN", 1000);

// Add with automatic trim
await redis.xadd("orders", "MAXLEN", "~", 1000, "*",
  "orderId", "ORD-5678",
  "status", "created"
);

// Trim entries older than a specific ID
await redis.xtrim("orders", "MINID", "~", "1681234567890-0");

// Check stream length
const length = await redis.xlen("orders");
```
